    <exercise id="fs-id1931391" type="problems-exercises">
<problem id="fs-id2684015">
 <para id="import-auto-id2599260">Suppose you measure the terminal voltage of a 1.585-V alkaline cell having an internal resistance of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>100</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{0 "." "100"  %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> by placing a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mtext>-k</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{1 "." "00""-k" %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> voltmeter across its terminals. (See <link target-id="import-auto-id1349482"/>.) (a) What current flows? (b) Find the terminal voltage. (c) To see how close the measured terminal voltage is to the emf, calculate their ratio.</para><figure id="import-auto-id1349482"><media id="import-auto-id2973101" alt="The figure shows a circuit diagram that includes a battery with an internal resistance r and a voltmeter connected across its terminals. The current I is shown by an arrow pointing in a clockwise direction.">
