<problem id="fs-id2441432">
  <para id="import-auto-id3037003">Suppose you measure the terminal voltage of a 3.200-V lithium cell having an internal resistance of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.15em"/><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{5 "." "00"  %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> by placing a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>00</m:mtext><m:mtext>-k</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{1 "." "00""-k" %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> voltmeter across its terminals. (a) What current flows? (b) Find the terminal voltage. (c) To see how close the measured terminal voltage is to the emf, calculate their ratio.</para></problem></exercise>

