    <exercise id="fs-id1915875" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2381548">
 <para id="import-auto-id3175370"><emphasis>Unreasonable Results</emphasis></para>
<para id="eip-id2671829">Suppose you have a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>40</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>0-Ω</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"40" "." 0- %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> galvanometer with a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>25</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>0-μA</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"25" "." 0-mA} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> sensitivity. (a) What resistance would you put in series with it to allow it to be used as a voltmeter that has a full-scale deflection for 0.500 mV? (b) What is unreasonable about this result? (c) Which assumptions are responsible?</para></problem></exercise>

    <exercise id="fs-id1990504" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id3094830">
 <para id="import-auto-id1972579"><emphasis>Unreasonable Results</emphasis></para>
<para id="eip-id2629742">(a) What resistance would you put in parallel with a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>40</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>0-Ω</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"40" "." 0- %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> galvanometer having a
<m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>25.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>0-μA</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:semantics></m:math> sensitivity to allow it to be used as an ammeter that has a full-scale deflection for <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow>
<m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>0-μA</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"10" "." 0 μA} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>? (b) What is unreasonable about this result? (c) Which assumptions are responsible?</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id2442989">
    <para id="import-auto-id2032269">(a) <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mo stretchy="false">−</m:mo><m:mtext>66</m:mtext></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mn>7</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mo stretchy="false">Ω</m:mo></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{-"66" "." 7  %OMEGA } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para><para id="import-auto-id2660410">(b) You can’t have negative resistance.</para>
    <para id="import-auto-id1245691">(c) It is unreasonable that <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mn>G</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I rSub { size 8{G} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> is greater than <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:msub><m:mi>I</m:mi><m:mrow><m:mtext>tot</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:msub></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{I rSub { size 8{"tot"} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> (see <link target-id="import-auto-id2932271"/>). You cannot achieve a full-scale deflection using a current less than the sensitivity of the galvanometer.</para></solution>
